{
  "answer": "**Slokantara**, *Chapter 1*, argues that nothing is without a flaw—even the finest things in nature and the gods themselves bear defects—and thus ordinary humans on earth must have them all the more.[^1]\n\nThe specific verse catalogues these flaws as follows:\n\n> *The lotus is full of thorns; the snowy mountain has its cold; the sandalwood tree is inhabited by serpents;*  \n> *The sun is fierce; the moon has a body stained by a hare; the ocean has salty water;*  \n> *Viṣṇu was a cowherd; Indra is exceedingly fickle; Śaṅkara has a blue throat;*  \n> *All these have flaws; how much more so will people on earth have flaws?* || 47 ||[^2]\n\n[^1]: *Slokantara*, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-c5d550).\n\n[^2]: *Slokantara*, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-9647e1).",
